[[0, 'I really enjoyed this book.'], [0, 'The concept of a man who had grown up on Mars and never seen another human until he was in his twenties is such a fun idea - and a rich canvas.'], [0, 'Watching Mike try to grok humans gave a Heinlein great opportunities to point out some of our faults - and our advantages.'], [0, "I think my favorite part of this book is the word 'grok'."], [0, "I would bet that there are deep discussions over the true meaning of this word - but I will contend that its closest meaning in English is 'to be enlightened about something'."], [0, 'If you grok God you have reached enlightenment.'], [0, 'If you grok music you truly understand in the way that Mozart understood it.'], [0, 'If you grok another person you love them.'], [0, 'If you grok programming then you truly love and are really good at programming - that, and you\'re also a probably a pretty big nerd for using a word like \'grok\' :) I used it in front of my girlfriend and she still hasn\'t forgiven me, since I had to explain that it was "a Martian word"!'], [0, "One thing that I grokked (yes I'm going to keep using it dammit) after finishing this book is that it is kind of a 60's manifesto for free love."], [0, "I wasn't alive in the 60's, but given everything I know about the 60's from movies, books, etc it seemed that my grokking was right."]]

[[0, 'A research institute discovers that some twins are able to communicate with telepathy between each other.'], [0, "It's not limited by the speed of light and offers a great chance for space exploration."], [0, 'One twin stays at home and the other is on board of a spaceship to explore new worlds.'], [0, "Characterization has never been Heinlein's strongest point and it shows here again but he is extremely good at writing believable adventure stories."], [0, 'I liked that the protagonist is no hero, he is selfish and still has to learn how to deal with his own problems and with other people.'], [0, "That's a big difference to Heinlein's later books where the protagonists cynically show off their superiority and bypass normal ways because they know the ropes."], [0, 'Not so here!'], [0, 'Actions and values are carefully evaluated from different sides.'], [0, "There were some minor things I didn't like."], [0, 'The twins have strange relationships, not the deep emotional bound that I assumed they always have.'], [0, "This allowed some plot twists that otherwise wouldn't have been possible."], [0, "I also found it strange to tell someone straight into his face that you don't like him."], [0, 'Heinlein touches interesting topics that never grow old.'], [0, 'I can recommend this book to every SF fan and especially to young readers.'], [0, 'Read Citizen of the Galaxy first and then this one and you will understand why the author is still held in high esteem.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'On the publication of this novel, Flaubert expressed concern that no one would care about Frederic, that the insipidity of the character would render the book uninteresting to most people.'], [0, 'This is, alas, an accurate self-criticism, and Henry James felt the same way.'], [0, 'Frederic is simply too dull, too vacuous a character to support spending 500 pages with him, no matter how well-written the pages are.'], [0, 'An ambitious novel, it is probably the closest thing that anyone has ever come to creating what Flaubert dreamed of creating-- a novel unified not by subject matter or plot, but by style alone.'], [0, "The book is a combination of semi-autobiography while paralleling the main character's various failed loves with the politics of the day."], [0, 'And his friends embody the various philosophies prevalent at the time.'], [0, 'So when our omniscient narrator disparages Frederic, Flaubert is disparaging himself to a certain extent.'], [0, 'As with "Madame Bovary," Flaubert raises questions about the nature of love-- and shows the power of love to destroy.'], [0, 'When one hides behind love to avoid maturing, to avoid being involved in the other concerns of the world, one becomes less human than even someone who never pursues love at all.'], [0, "At the beginning, Frederic's lack of sympathy at his uncle's death-- delighting in the news of his passing, as it meant he inherited a fortune-- is amusing."], [0, 'By the end, when he is weeping over Madame Arnoux rather than the death of his own son, he is monstrous.'], [0, 'He becomes despicable simply by his failure to be changed by the circumstances that demand it.'], [0, 'The lack of suspense and the long study of politics (which I admit I know next to nothing about) made this book something of a chore for me.'], [0, 'However, the prose in this pessimistic work is superb as only Flaubert can render it, and searingly insightful as to the human condition.'], [0, "In addition, the whole concept of unredemptive love, of love as a form of 'projected narcissism,' of love as a shell to contain one's ulterior motives, an obsessive delusion masquerading as a 'spark of the divine'-- is a theme that is vastly underrepresented in literature."]]

'Full disclsoure: this review is being written before I have read the sequel.'], [0, "Simmons' style has not changed much from the Hyperion Cantos."], [0, 'It is functional and descriptive, but nothing more.'], [1, 'Despite the amount of time spent describing certain structures, such as the various apparatuses on the rings , I still felt at a loss as to what they looked like, which means that those sometimes extended passages were complete wastes of time.'], [0, 'Similarly, as other reviewers have noted, Simmons goes into pseudo-scientific jargon describing various constructs and then has his characters claim ignorance at the end anyway.'], [0, 'This is not hard sci-fi, so those instances are particularly irritating.'], [0, 'A final complaint is that there are way too many descriptions of "boobs" and female anatomy that serve no interesting purpose.'], [0, 'The main character is a playboy, but the significance of that is never mentioned, nor do the other characters even seem to be aware of that presumably defining trait.'], [0, "Simmon's unique prosaic strength in this work is his emulation of his inspirations."], [0, 'The novel begins with a twist on the opening lines of the Iliad, there are frequent references to Proust, Shakespeare, Nabokov.'], [0, 'Toward the end of the book, we get a remarkable description of battle arrays that feels lifted from the Homeric epics.'], [0, "Given Simmons' literary project, there are necessary flourishes."], [0, 'There are plenty of themes and content in the book.'], [0, 'In the plot itself, we encounter transhumanism, self-aware AI, biospheres and noospheres, anti-Semitism (in a world without Jews, no less), free will, intellectual and cultural degredation that is explicitly compared to the society of the eloi in The Time Machine, control of humanity by outside forces, terraforming and space colonization, rebellion, to name some of many.'], [0, 'The reader is also treated -- or subjected -- to literary analysis of Shakespeare and Proust by various cyborgs.'], [0, 'Whether their metafictional conclusions tie into the plot can only be determined in the second book; they certainly seem disconnected in the first.'], [0, "Simmons' characterization is decent, but not as solid as in the Hyperion Cantos."], [0, 'Daeman undergoes a nice character arc, and while Ada and Harman and Hannah have personalities, they generally have defining traits ("curiosity," "love," etc.).'], [0, 'I do not need internal psychological monologs in all my novels, so I was fine with the distinctions between characters.'], [0, 'The motivations of the characters are clear, and while the protagonist Hockenberry -- a revived Homeric scholar with little memory of his previous life -- is pretty obviously a reader stand-in, he still managed to take clear (if sometimes inexplicably misguided) actions on his own agency.'], [0, 'I cannot go into too much more discussion of the themes because they are merely set up in this doorstopper; all of the resolution will hopefully come in the second volume.'], [0, 'The book seems to face two weaknesses of plot: the first is that it is needlessly long.'], [0, 'The moravec journey is dragged out as much as possible with little reward.'], [1, "Hockenberry's antics are sometimes extraneous or redundant (how many times does he need to sleep with Helen in great detail ?"], [0, '), and the old-style human plot takes forever to get going.'], [0, 'Concision, especially when only at the end of the book does anything really happen, would have been greatly appreciated here.'], [0, 'Second, all of the literary allusions feel arbitrary.'], [0, 'The premise of a Trojan War happening for mysterious circumstances again in the future (or the past?'], [0, 'or...) is great.'], [0, 'Having characters discuss literature is great, especially if those digressions have relevance to the larger plot (cf.'], [0, 'the pirate narrative in Watchmen).'], [0, 'Having absurdly specific allusions form the core of the plot without explanation is less tolerable.'], [0, 'Partway through the book is some mumbo-jumbo about alternate universes in which works created by genuises become real.'], [0, 'Perhaps this is the source of the Greeks, Trojans, gods, and Propsero/Ariel/Caliban?'], [0, 'Of course, nothing is settled, but the question arises of how Simmons feels qualified to select who is a genius and why, in-universe, those particular literary constructs have been reified.'], [0, 'Why is the noosphere Prospero rather than Gatsby or Jean Valjean or King Arthur or Cao Cao or any other character?'], [0, "Were it merely arbitrary nomenclature selected Prospero's creator, I would be content."], [0, 'Yet Prospero and Caliban actually exhibit traits of their Shakespearean personalities, and the latter quotes extensively from Browning\'s "Caliban Upon Setebos."'], [0, 'This actually makes the entire situation less satisfying to me.'], [0, 'I think perhaps I would have been fine with either The Tempest or The Iliad being treated in the way they are in this novel separately, but when both are combined, I am asking myself what in-universe reason there is for the combination.'], [0, 'The Hyperion Cantos skirted this issue successfully by having more and less plot-defining allusions.'], [0, 'This book is the opposite, and therefore displeases me, at least in this regard.'], [0, 'Overall, a fine book, and I look forward to Olympos, but anyone looking for a definitive Simmons work should instead read the Hyperion Cantos.']]

column2: Longitude: The True Story of a Lone Genius Who Solved the Greatest Scientific Problem of His Time
review_sentences: [[0, "It's odd to imagine it now, but in the 18th century it was incredibly difficult to determine exactly where you were."], [0, 'On land, it was easy enough to resort to landmarks, but at sea, while finding latitude was easy, longitude was such a thorny problem that the British government offered PS20,000 (millions today) to the person who could provide a way to calculate it.'], [0, 'Enter John Harrison.'], [0, 'Harrison was a self-taught clockmaker (or a horologist), originally a carpenter, who built his first clock almost entirely of wood.'], [0, 'When he heard of the prize being offered, he decided that the best way would be to make a better clock.'], [0, 'Clocks at the time could lose up to 15 minutes a day, and were essentially useless if the pressure or temperature changed too much due to expansion and contraction of their internal components, which made them far too unreliable to use at sea.'], [0, 'His wooden clock had performed so well he was positive he could do it, given time, and he set to work.'], [0, "Of course, it wasn't that easy."], [0, "The scientific method is an excellent series of rules, but scientists are human and they certainly aren't Vulcans."], [0, 'Many of the members of the Board of Longitude, set up to award the prize and determine the accuracy of the solutions proposed, were astronomers who were invested in the use of astronomy to solve the problem of longitude and were skeptical that a mere "mechanical" would develop a proper solution.'], [0, 'Somewhat hilariously, there is a note that for the first five years, the board never met, because the prize was so high that they mostly just got worthless proposals that were clearly unhelpful, or crank ones like perpetual motion machines, which is a problem the US Patent Office still has.'], [0, "Anyway, the astronomical solution involves using the moon's position in relation to the stars and then comparing it to a set of charts that allow the navigator to determine their distance from a known reference point."], [0, 'This is essentially the same way clocks do it--the navigator measures local time and sees how different it is from the clock set in port.'], [0, 'And it works!'], [0, "Except that you need the charts, and several hours to look at the night sky and take the measurements, and the sky has to be clear, and so on, but it's actual SCIENCE!"], [0, 'And because of that, it took decades to get chronometers as standard practice on ships.'], [0, "This is more of an overview than a book, but for someone who knew essentially nothing about this series of events like I did, it's a good one."], [0, 'John Harrison has much more extensive biographies available, many of which are given in the bibliography at the end, and if nothing else, this made me more interested in reading one.'], [0, 'It did lose one star for the somewhat rambling nature of the ending.'], [0, 'After Harrison dies, the book tries to wrap up the story of the chronometer, but it jumps around between a couple different other clockmakers that it suddenly introduces and mostly lost my interest.'], [0, "If you're looking for a quick read about what, for centuries, was the greatest problem for maritime navigation, this is a pretty good choice, but if you want any real analysis or in-depth treatment, look elsewhere."]]

some of the scenes and passages were so beautiful and heartbreaking or philosophically rich."], [0, 'But so much of it was not actually about Anna and her affair.'], [0, "I would say most of the book is written through the point of view Levin (married to the sister of Anna's sister-in-law, so a very distant relation by marriage)."], [0, "The two of them don't even meet until about page 600 or so and then they only stay in each other's company for 5 pages."], [0, "I'm writing about their relationship or lack thereof to try and explain how Levin had basically nothing to do with Anna, and anytime Tolstoy wrote through his perspective, the book wasn't about Anna at all."], [0, "Now, all that's fine of course, but it made the novel jumpy to me."], [0, 'It seemed like there were two different novels going on: one about Levin and his philosophical/political qualms and one about Anna defying society.'], [0, 'With that being said, the parts about Anna or through her point of view were amazing.'], [0, 'I found that even when Anna herself was speaking, Tolstoy was able to make you love and hate her - just as society hated her and Vronsky, sometimes, loved her.'], [0, 'It was so beautiful because she fled her husband to be with Vronsky, thus sacrificing everything for him (friends, society, reputation, her son), but then in the end those things (and their destruction in her life) made her miserable.'], [0, "It's like Tolstoy was saying that no matter what women had a place and if they tried to defy that position in society or marriage, they couldn't find any happiness in life."], [0, 'Very moving.'], [0, 'The parts about Levin, however - which again was the brunt of the book - I found boring and tediously long (ten page scenes about hunting and farming - blagh).'], [0, "Overall I give it a four because of how powerful Anna's story was - especially in the end."], [0, 'So sad.']]

[[0, "Less ambitious authors would be content to dedicate their novel to the immediate premise of The Child in Time: the loss of a family's innocence and its hopes for recovery after the theft of a child."], [0, 'McEwan works here as he does in later, more widely known novels, with layered presentations of theme and a greater effort to explore the loss of childhood to those stolen into adulthood, and how parents are often stolen from their own lives by childbirth.'], [0, 'The decision to have a child becomes significant, and there are suggestions, more optimistic here, of the later novel,  On Chesil Beach, where the consequences of action (or inactivity) on later life are explored.'], [0, "McEwan writes beautifully of the awe in which children hold their parents, and of adults' recognition of individuality within their children."], [0, 'If you read this expecting a book of loss and recovery, I think you may miss the point: that life is ultimately defined by action over regret; and that there is no real recovery from loss every moment stolen.'], [0, 'The novel is as touching in portraying its adult relationships as it is those between parent and child.'], [0, 'A beautiful, complicated book that seeks to broaden its scope beyond the modern thirst for lives full of simply characterized regrets.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "Once again, I've destroyed my love for a book (although I do still like it)."], [0, "I first read The Last Temptation of Christ in '88, just before Martin Scorsese turned it into a movie, and I remember being blown away."], [0, "Unfortunately, my literary concerns were different back then; the me who read The Last Temptation of Christ over the last couple of weeks doesn't match the me who read it twenty-two years ago."], [0, 'I care more about consistency today.'], [0, 'I care more about character, theme and message.'], [0, "And beautiful prose...it just doesn't dazzle me like it used to."], [0, 'What I always loved about The Last Temptation of Christ was the way Nikos Kazantzakis gave us a mortal Jesus who struggled with his role as the Son of God.'], [0, 'I loved that he was tempted by Lucifer and truly felt that temptation.'], [0, "I loved that he was so weak that he needed Judas, his friend and his strength, to betray him so he could be crucified and die for man's sins."], [0, "But that wasn't Kazantzakis' The Last Temptation of Christ -- that was Scorsese's."], [0, "Kazantzakis' Jesus was bereft of free will."], [0, "Sure Lucifer's temptations preyed on Jesus' mind, but the power of God's coercion mooted Lucifer's attempts to corrupt Jesus."], [0, "Moreover, Jesus' weakness and Judas' strength were irrelevant."], [0, "God's hand fated their outcomes, and what I thought was the transcendent power of men choosing divine sacrifices was nothing more than foreordained game play."], [0, "They were God's pawns in a one-sided game that couldn't be lost, so the sacrifice that had made me love the novel for two decades was no sacrifice at all."], [0, 'I wish it were otherwise.'], [0, "I wish I still loved Kazantzakis' version of The Last Temptation of Christ, and that his sensual prose -- wonderfully translated by P.A."], [0, "Bien -- could overcome the annoying contradictions between Christ's words/thoughts and his actions."], [0, 'I wish the Jesus of the novel was the Jesus of the movie.'], [0, 'But my wishes are and will remain unfulfilled.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'What really impressed me about this book was its creativity, its scope and its plausibility.'], [0, 'It feels very authentic for a book about zombies.'], [0, 'Written in oral history style, this a a true panorama with a large cast of characters that surveys how dozens of countries reacted to a multi-stage zombie infestation.'], [0, 'Even from the vantage point of survivors reflecting back on personal experience, most of these vignettes are thrilling and moving.'], [0, "You'll read about large scale migrations north as survivors seek the comfort of freezing weather, dramatic military engagements, the breakdown of government and civil society as vigilante violence, illness and suicides ravage survivors, the secrets of the countries that weathered the apocalypse well (democracy is not necessary helpful to zombie fighting), and lots of other practical details."], [0, 'This is an ambitious and impressive work with some smart geopolitical and psychological commentary.'], [0, 'The fates of many countries are discussed, with particularly memorable discussions of America, Canada, China, Russia, South Africa, Israel, Cuba, Japan, and North Korea.'], [0, 'Minor nitpicks: I left this book without a clear sense of the timeline (i.e.'], [0, 'when the Zombie War began and ended, how long each stage was) and how far after the conclusion of large scale hostilities World War Z takes place.'], [0, "There are parts that make it seem like it takes place many years in the future, but the presence of interview subjects who lived through World War II means that it can't be that far ahead."], [0, 'Also, while I understand its inclusion, there were a few points where the high level of detail about military equipment/maneuvers made my eyes glaze over.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "After I finished the first volume of Proust's masterpiece, I did what I always do when I finish a book: I wrote a review."], [0, 'And, in truth, I ended up being a bit harsh and hyperbolic in that review; but I soon came to second-guess myself.'], [0, "For, although I can't say I exactly loved Swann's Way (I liked it), that book had, without my being aware of it, completely undermined everything I thought I knew about fiction."], [0, 'Unconsciously, imperceptibly, my whole concept of the novel had changed.'], [0, 'So it feels a bit dishonest of me to say anything negative about Proust; maybe all my negative sentiments are just a psychological defense mechanism, meant to shield myself from feeling overwhelmed by the influence Proust has exerted over me.'], [0, "Maybe I'm just feeling the literary equivalent of an Oedipus complex, and am striking out at the father who nurtured me."], [0, 'Still, even if we know we are deluding ourselves, we must, in the end, accept the delusions, for we have nothing to replace them with.'], [0, 'So here are mine.'], [0, "I love Proust's style, but I am bored by his subject--love."], [0, 'Perhaps you will think me odd, but I find love a very boring topic for art.'], [0, "I've heard too many love songs, read too many love poems, listened to too many lover's complaints."], [0, "It's not that I've sought these out, mind you, but that they pervade our culture; and it's a cultural obsession that I've always failed to understand."], [0, 'Love is, after all, an emotion--a very fine and very beautiful emotion, of course, but an emotion just the same.'], [0, "I don't like reading odes to happiness or listening to songs about feeling lonely."], [0, "Emotions are self-evident; they don't need to be analyzed--they simply are."], [0, "I don't think many people will agree with me, but that's how I've always felt--so that's that."], [0, 'To be fair, this book is far from a sappy love song.'], [0, "In many ways, it's precisely the reverse: it does not attempt to evoke the feeling of love, but to analyze it."], [0, "In Proust's hands, a pen becomes a scalpel."], [0, 'He anatomizes every instant; he conducts autopsies of every slight memory.'], [0, "This book can be read as an account of exploratory surgery on Love's cadaver, performed with a steady hand and a cynical eye."], [0, 'But I must confess that even this bores me.'], [0, 'Am I a philistine?'], [0, 'Am I unfeeling?'], [0, 'Perhaps.'], [0, 'But, really, why is this phenomenon so fascinating to so many?'], [0, "I'd rather read a 500 page book analyzing our feelings of hunger."], [0, "It wouldn't be so different; a single trip through a supermarket could be as exciting as the trip to Balbec:"], [0, 'I saw, sitting on the shelf, a little band of apples; and these apples, which lay there so innocently, so playfully, so indistinguishable from one another, at once absorbed my total attention.'], [0, 'I saw them there, sitting in the harsh light of the supermarket, their waxy skin gleaming attractively; and this gleam of light awakened in my stomach rumblings and stirrings, which, as I reflected, must have existed there all along, dormant, waiting to be awakened by the sight of some fruit.'], [0, 'But as I reached out my hand, picking up the apple that most caught my fancy, my expectations were shattered; it felt so weightless in my hand, and its waxy skin felt so much like plastic, that my desire was immediately destroyed, my hunger abated, and I put back the apple--thrown back once more into that confusion of hunger, knowing that I wanted food, but not knowing what I wanted to eat.'], [0, "(Alright, that's probably a horrid parody, but you get my drift.)"], [0, "In short, I cannot say that I loved this book; but I can't blame Proust for my particularities of taste."], [0, "I did, however, very much like it; for, even if the subject bored me, it's impossible not to be amazed by the depth of intelligence betrayed in every sentence, the brilliance lurking in every line."], [0, 'And, in my heart, I suspect that I will, once again, come to reproach myself for being harsh and hyperbolic in a review of Proust.'], [0, 'My complaints are the complaints of a whining child, annoyed at his mother opening the blinds, letting the bright sunlight come streaming in.'], [0, 'After all, it takes a long time for your eyes to adjust.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "This is my entire life's most favorite novel."], [0, 'Love in the Time of Cholera is a love story told in a degree so timeless and real yet so magical and lyrical it sings in your heart for a long, long time.'], [0, 'In this novel, Gabriel Garcia Marquez answers two simple questions about love: What would you do for love?'], [0, 'Everything.'], [0, 'How long will you wait?'], [0, 'Forever.'], [0, 'Oh how he answers those questions so well, deliciously, perfectly, comically, madly, innocently well.'], [0, 'There is this kind of love which is undying and celebrated, one that is tested by cruel time and stands above all crises of life, moreover defying them with the infallible ardor and power of two hearts, of stability, of happiness.'], [0, 'This kind of love makes the world go round, it puts the smile on the sun on a sunny day, alive and jumping, it paints the rainbow with a gradient of colors for everybody to marvel at.'], [0, 'This love is an endless ocean, full of everything, calm and sometimes uncontrollably furious, but nonetheless life-giving.'], [0, 'There is another one, love as a disease but does not permit the beholder of it to suffer the ultimate consequence which is death for this love is as equally undying, unrequited, stubborn, painfully throbbing mad pulsations in the tired heart which would never ever experience the peaceful happiness for almost a lifetime.'], [0, 'This love is the sole driving force of a man who is consumed by a persistently blind rage towards a foolish dash to achieve dreams of great heights but in the end achieves nothing for the very simple reason that the core, the reasons for his actions will never be reciprocated and will always be rejected.'], [0, 'This love is the void of the universe, motivationally chaotic, perfectly dark, but also has everything.'], [0, 'This love is unreachable.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'Bret Easton Ellis\' depiction of Los Angeles can be best summed up by the title of one of the city\'s premiere punk acts: "How Could Hell Be Any Worse?".'], [0, "Ellis' schtick throughout his career has been that he is at heart a staunch moralist; the hip, stylish lives of his characters are inevitably depicted as nihilistic, lost, and drug-addled, and they are by extension symbolic condemnation of the lives of pathetic rich Gen Xers, both in youth and (by LTZ sequel Imperial Bedrooms) middle age."], [0, 'By his later career this particular trope has worn thin, but Less Than Zero is written with the breathless depth of passion that only a brilliant young writer on his first novel can muster.'], [0, 'This is ironic, of course, because the characters of Less Than Zero have none of that passion; they flit from party to party, club to club, snorting coke and having indiscriminate sex with each other.'], [0, "They're the children of the L.A."], [0, 'upper crust, loaded down with trust funds and fancy cars.'], [0, 'Their parents are absent, off on business or simply on permanent vacation.'], [0, "It's a running joke throughout the novel that one of the characters only knows the whereabouts of her mother through the reporting of Variety magazine."], [0, 'They have too much money and nothing to drive interest; the most used descriptor of the extras in the backgrounds of the scenes is "bored".'], [0, "There's nothing going on."], [0, 'Clay, the protagonist, has trouble describing what he does all day, mainly because what he does is hang out with amoral rich kids who do large amounts of cocaine.'], [0, 'The other characters in the book are mainly beyond redemption.'], [0, "Clay's friend Trent, by the end, finds excitement in a dead body in an alley, a snuff film, and a real-life kidnap-and-rape situation brought about by their coke dealer."], [0, 'His best friend Julian has descended into heroin addiction and prostitution.'], [0, "He can't relate to his high school girlfriend Blair anymore."], [0, "He tries desperately throughout to feel something, and the joke here is that he's the only one who seems to be able to feel anything."], [0, "He can't put his finger on it, but he cries several times, feels a form of guilt and remorse over the death of a coyote, and is the only person he can remember who felt concern over the declining health of his grandmother."], [0, "He wants to plumb the depths of absolute darkness that his friends are caught in but he freaks out when he finally encounters it; he may be friends with these people, but he's not quite one of them."], [0, 'Less Than Zero is impressive as a debut novel, especially considering Ellis was 21 when he wrote it and still attending Bennington College (or is that Camden, heh heh heh).'], [0, 'While the themes that it presents - the children of the rich and famous are set on paths that are at once nihilistic and incredibly sad - are basically cliche today, in 1985 we were not having our noses rubbed in it on a daily basis.'], [0, 'Hence the New York Times review, which claimed it was the "most disturbing novel" the reviewer had ever read.'], [0, "I see a lot of reviews on GR that don't seem to understand that the book was not written in an age when reality TV opened the window on the misdeeds of the celebrity set, and it's worth noting that for most of us it was our first glance into the seedy world of the upper echelon of Generation X."]]

[[0, '***WARNING: This review contains a potential spoiler in terms of plot and character.'], [0, 'Read at your peril.'], [0, "I wish I could say that I tried harder to get through Pet Semetary before giving it up, that I carried it with me, that I read it in those stolen moments of banality, which I do with most books, but the fact is I didn't."], [0, "And that says much about why I've decided to put it down unfinished."], [0, "It's not that the story is a bad idea."], [0, "Stephen King's story of the Creed family -- new to Maine and a life near Bangor -- is pretty clever and has enough going on that it should be interesting."], [0, 'They move in, they argue about how to explain death to their children, their cat dies and is born again with a mean streak, then their (thanks, Kelly ;)) son Gage dies and all hell breaks loose.'], [0, "It should be creepy (I remember the movie being creepy when I was young), and it probably would be if I could go on, but I just don't care."], [0, "When I am reading it I enjoy it well enough (it has been my walking home from jogging book), but once I put it down I don't really want to go back."], [0, "I'm not sure why, although I think it might be have something to do with it just not frightening me."], [0, 'Indeed, nothing by King frightens me...ever...!and when I am reading a horror I want more than creepy and readable, I want freaky-to-the-core, make-it-hard-to-sleep-late-at-night, compel-me-to-keep-going-in-spite-of-myself scary.'], [0, 'And King never seems to do that.'], [0, 'So...with another whimper ends my third attempt at reading King.'], [0, 'I am sure I will try again a few years from now (something always pulls me back), but after book one of The Dark Tower underwhelmed me and Pet Semetary went onto my unfinished shelf, I realized it was time to concede my indifference and move on once again.'], [0, "Sorry King fans (especially you Helen)...he's just not my bag."]]

[[0, 'I hate novels where parenting is questioned, simply because I too often find myself thinking, "Well I would never do THAT."'], [0, "I then have to do the whole knock-on-wood routine and hope that I didn't just invite divine retribution for being too judgmental."], [0, "So it was with Jodi Picoult's novel My Sister's Keeper."], [0, 'After reading the summary of the novel, I knew that I would never make the choices that the parents shown did.'], [0, 'After reading the novel, I found myself questioning what I might really do if my child was facing death.'], [0, "In case you missed the summary, My Sister's Keeper is the story of Anna, a thirteen year old girl genetically conceived to be a match for her leukemia-positive sister."], [0, "Within minutes of her birth, she was a donor for Kate, sharing her cord blood to save her sister's life."], [0, 'By the time she is thirteen, when the novel takes place, she has been in the hospital almost as much as Kate, donating things such as blood and bone marrow.'], [0, 'After being asked to donate a kidney, she seeks legal emancipation from her parents.'], [0, 'And so the story begins.'], [0, 'One of the things that bugged me was the chapter-by-chapter switch of the point of view.'], [0, 'It was very well handled and, once I got past the irritation stage, I had to admit that it helped the story along.'], [0, 'And so we skip through the minds of Anna, her lawyer, her court-appointed guardian ad litem, her brother, her father, and her mother - in short, everyone close to Anna except her sister.'], [0, 'Each of these perspectives is given in the present, with the notable exception of her mother.'], [0, "Instead, we trace the mother's path of learning that her daughter has leukemia, and what decisions led her (and Anna) to the current moment."], [0, "This, too, was initially annoying, but proved well-chosen; I'm not sure the same impact would have been made if we simply had the mom looking back."], [0, 'It would have been far easier to judge her at that point than it was to see her experiencing her pain.'], [0, "In fact, it was from Sara's perspective that I learned the most, and that I questioned myself."], [0, 'If my young daughter, the light of my life, was threatened with death, how far would I go to save her?'], [0, "I don't think that I honestly would have even thought up the idea of conceiving a child specifically for that purpose, but what do you do once the idea has been planted?"], [0, 'Furthermore, it is clear that Sara loves and cherishes Anna, even as she worries incessantly over Katie.'], [0, 'True, she neglects her, but she also neglects her son, who had been born prior to the diagnosis, turning most of her attention to her sick child.'], [0, 'And though this also made me pass judgement, it also made me wonder - would I be able to balance my attention on all my children if one were struggling through a life-long illness?'], [0, 'How easy would it be to make small decisions that hurt the others to save the one?'], [0, 'In short, I hated this well-written, well-developed, well-plotted book because it made me think.'], [0, 'The moral and religious side of me rejects the notion of a test-tube baby conceived for a specific purpose, but the mother in me wonders.'], [0, "If my child were starving, how easy would it be to remain true to my moral perspectives and not steal (assuming, of course, the government weren't around to save me)?"], [0, 'If someone threatened my child, how far would I go to protect them?'], [0, 'In short, when it comes down to crunch time, how true would I stay?'], [0, 'To fall asleep, I have to assure myself that I would, of course, be perfect in all things.'], [0, 'And then knock soundly on the nearest wood, and pray I never have to find out.']]

[[0, 'This review was written in the late nineties (just for myself), and it was buried in amongst my things until today, when I uncovered the journal it was written in.'], [0, 'I have transcribed it verbatim from all those years ago (although square brackets indicate some additional information for the sake of readability).'], [0, 'It is one of my lost reviews.'], [0, "So much to say ... what's the most important?"], [0, "Well, Frazier's novel seems a throwback to the American naturalist movement, incorporating elements of historiography."], [0, "He's created a story where all of the obstacles and aids during Inman's journey are elemental, even when human."], [0, 'From the goat lady to Teague to snowstorms to the river escape, all the forces arrayed against Inman are forces of nature.'], [0, 'Inman, the tired man, overcomes.'], [0, 'But then Frazier creates a feminist awakening tale with Ada, wherein the natural forces are freshly discovered and take on a power evoked in the acts of using, naming, cataloging and learning.'], [0, 'His unifying image is birds.'], [0, 'For every feeling, every moment, a bird acts as an illuminating image.'], [0, 'The falcon, the heron, the buzzards and the crows are all important to Cold Mountain.'], [0, 'And the ending fits.'], [1, "Inman's death , Ada's life, and their daughter give Cold Mountain perfect symmetry."], [0, "It's a crime if it doesn't win the Pulitzer."]]

imagine a book teaching a little girl.'], [0, "But Beka doesn't really need to work to get what she wants."], [0, 'I thought we were going to get a really nice year of "Puppyhood" (Puppy is a pretty gaggable title to deal with for an entire book, just weird and kind of obnoxious) rife with hard work and setbacks and Beka finding out she\'s not so hot and finally she\'ll be worthy of a little respect and admiration and...oh wait, she just waltzed through that, didn\'t she?'], [0, "I mean, her magic jumps her over a bunch of hurdles and lets her get magic special information through birds, so she doesn't have to investigate all that hard."], [0, "She's from the gutter but she's the ward of the Lord Provost, so she doesn't have to battle the confines of her station."], [0, 'In fact, the low birth seems to help her most of the time.'], [0, "And instead of letting Cooper's shortcomings rear their ugly heads in crucial moments (see: Kel's vertigo, Alanna's temper), Pierce pretty much literally lays them on the line in the first diary entry and they're hardly seen again except as comic relief."], [0, "So she's super stubborn, pretty good at all her training, has a kickass memory, and has special magic nobody else has got that helps her do her job even better than she already does it."], [0, "Where's the hardworking weakness-overcoming heroine I expected here?"], [0, "Then there's the first-person point of view."], [0, "It was certainly the right stylistic choice for this story, but because it's not Pierce's MO it reads a little clumsy at times."], [0, "That introductory description passage was cringeworthy, like Beka's reading right off a character sheet about herself."], [0, 'I found the street slang more difficult to deal with than fun as a mode of narration.'], [0, 'I\'ve about had it with "mots" and "coves", and it\'s only book one of the trilogy.'], [0, "So I'm hoping that Beka's going to have to work harder in the future, and I'm hoping the diary format will chafe a little less next time."], [0, "Still, I really like Pierce as an author, and I know there's a potential for Beka to really take off and grab my admiration."], [0, "She's just got to work for it a little."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'I had to look up "geek" because it surely didn\'t mean the detailed interest of , say, a computer geek.'], [0, 'So I learned the carnival meaning.'], [0, 'Luckily the really gross and bloody part occurred only briefly at the beginning.'], [0, 'The next oddity was the father deciding to produce his own freak show for the carnival (based on his seeing horticultural variety at the International Test Rose Garden).'], [0, 'The mother dutifully took drugs to alter her offspring.'], [0, 'Their living children were four: Arty with fins for arms and legs; Elly and Iphy, the Siamese twins; Oly, the hunchbacked, dwarf narrator; and Chick the youngest, with his special powers.'], [0, 'Had it not been a group read, I might have stopped there.'], [0, 'However, I remembered a comment of a professor about other novels with "grotesques": What could the author say through them that couldn\'t be said through more average characters?'], [0, 'I decided to read a bit more through that frame.'], [0, 'Then the next chapter captured my attention with its narrative strategy of jumping into the future with Oly and her daughter Miranda.'], [0, 'Several events are revealed that make a reader wonder how they happened.'], [0, 'That same strategy is used a few more times, like a carrot to keep one reading.'], [0, 'For the first two thirds of the book, the pacing was very effective.'], [0, "Then the notes of a reporter/participant were introduced, and while they provided important information that Oly, the narrator, couldn't have known, they dragged the pace considerably."], [0, 'Also the very ending of the book, while motivated, seemed to take too long.'], [0, 'It also left me wondering to what extent it was a change in her character instead of an extension.'], [0, 'I have not yet answered the What could be said question.'], [0, 'First hypothesis, something about disability issues.'], [0, 'Did not hold up.'], [0, 'Second hypothesis, something about minorities.'], [0, 'The carnival provided a sort of ghetto where deformities were normal; however, the carnival was dependent on the money of the norms buying tickets.'], [0, "Oly didn't feel odd till she no longer lived in the carnival setting."], [0, 'One group member read an interview with the author and learned she is an environmentalist and is anti-war.'], [0, "Perhaps the father's manipulation is an extreme of the various pollutants in our atmosphere, food, and water."], [0, "And there was one paragraph in the reporter's notes where Arty ponders how people could criticize his followers who are maimed by choice and not criticize war with the injuries it produces."], [0, 'Maybe.'], [0, 'And is it really choice when there is cult-like power in the leader and manipulation?'], [0, "I feel the need to think more on the followers' willingness to endure amputation and what it might say about other things we readers may be willing to give up and for what."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'Andrew Compton is a British serial killer jailed for his grisly crimes.'], [0, 'He loved the dead, and I mean LOVED them, so much that he sought out young men, druggies and the like, who he believed wanted to die, and then he killed them.'], [0, 'He loved death so much that after years of imprisonment and a diagnosis of HIV, he decides to try to stop his own heart, and that is how he ends up being pronounced dead and shipped elsewhere for an autopsy and escapes prison.'], [0, 'He might be a famous serial killer, but everyone believes he is dead and this was a body snatching.'], [0, "Meanwhile, in New Orleans, we meet Jay, who lives off his family's wealth and for whom serial killing runs in his blood, and Tran, a young man who recently broke up with his longtime boyfriend Luke, a writer with full-blown AIDs."], [0, "Tran has a crush on Jay, Jay doesn't want to kill Tran because he's a local, and Luke is still obsessed with Tran, a situation exacerbated by Andrew's arrival in New Orleans and the instant connection he feels with Jay."], [0, "I still remember the beauty of Brite's language from Lost Souls, and while this book is not about vampires, the lush New Orleans setting and the homoeroticism (seriously, there are no female characters) would probably appeal to fans of Anne Rice's Vampire Chronicles."], [0, "This, however, is strictly about murder (not vampire murder), and it goes deep into uncomfortable detail, so if you aren't into things getting too graphic or gory then you might want to skip this one."], [0, 'But if you think you can handle it, the language will likely draw you in.'], [0, 'I found the first person narration of Andrew strange considering the third-person narration of Tran, Jay, and Luke, but it highlights how Andrew was outside of this drama playing out, being more of a catalyst and observer, and lover of the dead.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'I thank this book, because when I received it as a gift, I thought "Oh, I should read The Brothers Karamazov first, so that I understand any similarities/references."'], [0, "And that was a great book that I probably wouldn't have read without this nudging."], [0, "HOWEVER, this book has pretty much nothing to do with the other one; the similarities are - 4 brothers, each a different type (intellectual, religious, rabble-rouser, which very loosely match those in Karamazov, but the last brother in Karamazov was an evil idiot, and the last brother in K is the narrator, and he's kind of boring.)"], [0, "And, I'd say, that's where the similarity ends."], [0, "The dad doesn't get murdered, the mom is alive and present, there are also two younger sisters, they don't fight over a woman, etc."], [0, "Thematically, they aren't really similar, either."], [0, 'This book is very religious, and has a lot of baseball.'], [0, "I don't like baseball, so those parts were a bit of a slog for me, although it was mostly OK since the baseball could have been anything that someone is passionate about, so I kind of mentally substituted other things so I could relate (like wine-drinking."], [0, "I'm passionate about that)."], [0, 'I find the religious aspect interesting, because it was such a struggle for all the characters, but pretty much all of them found some kind of peace/faith by the end.'], [0, "It didn't simplify the spiritual struggle, and wasn't dogmatic."], [0, "So that's good."], [0, 'Other than that, this could be viewed as a typical "family saga" book, along the lines of Poisonwood Bible.'], [0, 'The characters were well differentiated, believable, each typifying a different path (through life?'], [0, 'to grace?)'], [0, 'And I read the last 100 pages in one night, so the end really gets engaging.'], [0, 'And it did make me cry.']]

review_sentences: [[0, '"My life like an old turnip: several places at once going bad."'], [0, 'Who Will Run the Frog Hospital?'], [0, 'is a look back at what the publishing industry euphemistically calls "young adulthood" by a writer who, during her own years on the young side of adulthood, preferred to dwell on life\'s inglorious middle.'], [0, 'While Moore refrains from some of the snappier crutches of the genre, she does demonstrate a fantastic ear for the pithy truths of those looking upon the grown-up world for the first time as near-peers.'], [0, '"Once you had seen enough people go through your register you realized everyone was the same: they looked the same, said the same things; they were all the same."'], [0, 'Her main character, Berie, is a teenager working at an amusement park in her hometown in upstate New York.'], [0, 'Berie unequivocally adores her friend Sils.'], [0, "Berie is a lowly cashier, while Sils' good looks and confidence have earned her a coveted role as a princess hostess at the same amusement park."], [0, "Suffice it to say, Berie and Sils' friendship does not survive the summer, although there is no outright betrayal such as those that occur weekly on teen soaps."], [0, 'Instead, boys and money and life happen.'], [0, "Looking back, years later, from a lonely dinner in Paris with her husband, Berie sees in her friendship with Sils, despite its hiccups and small hurts, love in the purest form she's ever known."], [0, "The style is quietly autobiographical here when compared with the light farce of A Gate at the Stairs, and yet Berie's voice is sharper than Tessie Keltjin's."], [0, '"Go placidly.'], [0, 'What a crock."'], [0, "As a result, Berie's frustrations and impatience with the start and stop progress of young adulthood cut deeper, in the end, as well."]]

[[0, 'This is one of those rare examples of the movie being better than the book.'], [0, 'Yeah.'], [0, 'I somehow managed to get through it, but this book was like one never-ending series of mood-setting lists.'], [0, 'An example:'], [0, '"Sally thought long and hard each time she hung up the phone.'], [0, "She thought about the girl in the drugstore and the sound of Antonia's footsteps on the stairs when she went to bed without a good-night hug."], [0, "She thought about Michael's life and his death, and about every second they had spent together."], [0, 'She considered each of his kisses and all the words he had ever said to her.'], [0, 'Everything was still gray-- the paintings Antonia brought home from school and slipped beneath her door, the flannel pajamas Kylie wore on chilly mornings, the velvet curtains that kept the world at bay.'], [0, "But now Sally began to order things in her mind-- grief and joy, dollars and cents, a baby's cry and the look on her face when you blew her a kiss on a windy afternoon."], [0, 'Such things might be worth something, a glance, a peek, a deeper look."'], [0, 'I count 4 lists in just one paragraph.'], [0, 'Within the next page, the total of similar lists goes up to 8.'], [0, 'In two pages.'], [0, 'This kind of writing feels sloppy when it is used beyond the beginning stages of scene setting, and when it is almost the only way the author seems to able to convey meaning it becomes teeth-gnashingly annoying.'], [0, "Add to this a complete lack of momentum and a generally meandering story line and you get a sad face (or maybe bitch face if I'm being honest) and a thumbs down from me."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'I have read Dragons of Winter Night a number of times since it was first published, and it has always been my favourite of the Chronicles.'], [0, 'This time I just finished reading it out loud to my four year olds.'], [0, 'A long undertaking, and one that was necessarily sporadic.'], [0, "Some nights we read, others we didn't, and how much we read was dependent on levels of sleepiness, focus and interest."], [0, 'But it was well worth the effort because my kids loved the story, and I can see it helping to expand their imaginations.'], [0, "This time through I also nailed down the main reason I love the Chronicles, and why it is still one of the best fantasy series ever inspired by Dungeons and Dragons -- the way in which it undercuts fantasy's usual racial hierarchies."], [0, 'One of the major problems I have long had with fantasy is the inherent racism that fantasy perpetuates.'], [0, 'Fantasy generally entrenches the concept of "good" and "evil" races (which even Dragonlance can\'t entirely escape), and this, in turn, leads to a hierarchy of races with the Elves as the "superior race" and some of the monstrous humanoid races as the "inferior races."'], [0, 'This scares me.'], [0, 'It scares me because when I bring this flaw up in discussion of Tolkien or Lewis or other "great" fantasy writers, people fight me passionately and refuse to recognize that a problem even exists.'], [0, 'It frightens me that most people who recognize the issue don\'t see anything wrong with racial hierarchies in fantasy (usually tossing out the old confection "it\'s only a story" as an argument).'], [0, 'It scares me because all of this also entrenches a frighteningly simplistic vision of good and evil.'], [0, "A black and white world view that simply doesn't exist and makes us capable of evil because we are sure of our own goodness."], [0, 'But Dragonlance makes race an issue, and no race is immune to evil deeds.'], [0, 'We have bad knights, bad Qualinesti elves, bad Silvanesti elves, bad and good dragons, heroic but racist dwarves, a bastard half-elf that no one can accept, tribal barbarians fighting through their prejudices towards the civilized world, a lover and friend of the heroes in charge of the Dragonarmies, and a pseudo-evil wizard who saves them all.'], [0, "There is very little black and white in Dragonlance, although it still appears in the forms of Paladine (Fizban) and Takhisis, and unlike other fantasy series -- even the great ones but particularly others in the D&D ouevre (see the Drizzt Do'Urden series) -- it is filled with far more shades of gray."], [0, 'It may seem like a pulpy little distraction, but the Dragons of Winter Night, and the entire Chronicles, is more than that.'], [0, 'It is series that can help to shape a new vision of ethics in fantasy literature.'], [0, "And I hope that's something my kids take away from the experience."], [0, 'I will do my best to make sure they do.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "Since joining goodreads, I've been baffled by the Neil Gaiman love fest."], [0, "American Gods, Neverwhere, Stardust, The Graveyard Book, they appear to be universally loved, and I've been skeptical of this emotion that borders on worship."], [0, "These books are good and all, and I recognize their general accessibility, but I don't personally find any of them mind blowing literature."], [0, "Gaiman's prose is no match for China Mieville's or Iain M. Banks' or Ursula LeGuin's (and countless others who write speculative fiction), and the way he recasts mythology into contemporary settings is more clever than inspired."], [0, 'The love accorded Gaiman, therefore, feels disproportionate to the quality of his work - at least to me.'], [0, "Lately, however, I've been reminded that I once loved Neil Gaiman, and that reminder was my return to The Sandman Preludes and Nocturnes."], [0, "Like his other fine work, The Wolves in the Walls, The Sandman series plays to Gaiman's greatest strength: his ability to conjure beautiful images from artists."], [0, 'But it also elevates many of the things that Gaiman is usually only able to do adequately.'], [0, 'His writing, when confined by thought and dialogue bubbles, is inspired (mostly because its goal is to be natural and believable rather than aspiring to literary greatness); his contemporizing of mythology is much more palatable (happening, as it does, in a comic book universe predisposed to gods and heroes); and his naturally cinematic pacing works better in a graphic format.'], [0, "Yes, indeed...graphic novels are Neil Gaiman's best form."], [0, 'Sleep of the Just - This may be the greatest first issue of a comic ever written.'], [0, 'The capture of Morpheus/Dream/Sandman (or whichever name of his you prefer), the sleeping sickness, his inevitable (and beautifully patient) escape and vengeance guarantees that any fan of fantasy or comic books or fantasy and comic books must continue with the series.'], [0, 'Even better, though, Sleep of the Just could have been its own stand-alone issue, and that would have been good enough.'], [0, 'There are few single issues of a comic that are so fulfilling.'], [0, 'I buy it all, and everything I had to know was given to me.'], [0, 'Luckily, Gaiman left me with plenty beyond what I wanted to know.'], [0, "My personal favourite: the introduction of Sandman's helm."], [0, 'Killer.'], [0, "Imperfect Hosts - A kick ass follow up episode that includes a taste of Sandman's powers, the characters that populate his Dreamworld, and the beginning of his search for the three artefacts stolen when Burgess captured him instead of Death."], [0, 'This episode is most notable, however, for the way Gaiman weaves his Sandman into the existing universe of DC.'], [0, 'I am not a DC fan.'], [0, "I read Batman and Superman because they are cultural requirements, and what I know of the DC Universe is filtered through the pages of those books, but Sandman was a rare piece that warped and wefted its way into the DC universe without letting itself get bogged down in DC's usual shabbiness."], [0, 'Imperfect Hosts is where this all begins to happen.'], [0, 'Dream A Little Dream of Me - A weakened and vulnerable Morpheus is busy looking for his sandbag, the first of the three stolen artefacts that can restore him to his former splendour and power.'], [0, "So he tracks down John Constantine, the Hellblazer, who bought the sandbag years before and put it into storage, but the sandbag is gone, stolen by Constantine's ex-lover, Rachel, a heroin addict who needed money for a fix."], [0, 'She never got it; instead, the sandbag took control of her mind, throwing her into a forever nightmare that included the transformation of her father into a room sized, living, breathing, tortured, mass of flesh.'], [0, 'Dream a Little Dream of Me is a horror show that hints at the depths of nightmare Dream will combat in future issues, and it embeds Morpheus more deeply into the DC Universe.'], [0, "It's a satisfying chapter in Morpheus' rebirth, and this is where the patient build towards the story's literary quality begins."], [0, "A Hope In Hell - This is the one issue that really doesn't thrill me too much."], [0, "Morpheus goes to Hell and meets up with Lucifer, Beelzebub and Azazel - Hell's triumvirate of Dark Lords - demanding the return of his helm."], [0, 'He ends up dueling Choronzon for his helm in a "reality" battle.'], [0, 'Each takes a turn in the shape or form or concept of something or other.'], [0, "Each incarnation is slightly tougher than the opponent's until the victor's incarnation can't be beat."], [0, 'Morpheus defeats Choronzon as "hope," which totally sucks.'], [0, 'Hope?!'], [0, 'Please.'], [0, 'I can see hope as a stage in the battle, perhaps, but as the ultimate incarnation of victory?'], [0, 'No way.'], [0, "Hope can be good, but it's also an emotion that can derail thought and action -- and that makes hope potentially bad and self-defeating."], [0, 'Still, Lucifer was cool and his parting words about Dream give us plenty to look forward to in the series to come: "One day, my brothers...One day I shall destroy him."'], [0, "Passengers - A creepy start to the search for Morpheus' last artefact - the Ruby of Dreams."], [0, "A decrepit Doctor Destiny is sufficiently mad when he escapes Arkham Asylum, Morpheus runs into J'onn and Scott Free from the JLI, and the Doctor Destiny corrupted Ruby throws Morpheus into a catatonic stupor on the floor of a storage garage in the middle of nowhere, all setting the stage for the most terrifying chapter of Volume One:"], [0, '24 Hours - Bloody, nasty, marvelous.'], [0, 'Dreams in the hand of a corrupted man become corruption, and the whole Earth suffers.'], [0, "This is the best issue of The Sandman in Preludes and Nocturnes, so I'll let it speak for itself."], [0, 'But be warned: this one is not for the faint hearted.'], [0, "Sound and Fury - This is a satisfying resolution to Dream's return to power."], [0, 'Sandman shows John Dee mercy, he bestows the Earth with a night of pleasant dreams, and he returns to his Dreamscape to rebuild his kingdom.'], [0, "It's not quite as powerful as 24 Hours, but it does what it needs to do."], [0, 'The Sound of Her Wings - Death is a beautiful thing.'], [0, 'If there were no other reason to love Neil Gaiman, this realization would be enough because Death really is a beautiful thing -- both in the comic and at the end of our lives'], [0, "I'm glad I revisited Gaiman's greatest moment."], [0, 'Maybe now I can enjoy his new stuff more and appreciate him as much as so many of my friends do.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "One of the works that helped inspire Indiana Jones, the League of Extraordinary Gentlemen, and lord knows what all else, King Solomon's Mines may not be a staggering work of fiction, but it nonetheless shaped a lot of literature (and films!)"], [0, 'in the decades to come.'], [0, "With that in mind I embarked on Allan Quatermain's journey to the titular mines, although they feature primarily at the end of the journey."], [0, "In fact, all together I'd have to say the experience was a bit episodic: first there's the almost-deadly journey through the desert, the almost-deadly entanglements with the natives, the almost-deadly experience in the mines(I don't think anything I've said here will spoil the book for anyone, but I won't elaborate further)."], [0, 'For me that made this a book I read in chunks over a couple of weeks, rather than the kind of novel I devour as hard and fast as I can (see also The Hunger Games, Storm Front and the other Dresden Files books, etc).'], [0, "And that's perfectly fine!"], [0, "The novel is a great adventure and a lot of fun, and even if it's not Faulkner or James Joyce or whatever, it's not entirely mindless pulp, either."], [0, 'Quatermain is at once a lover of Africa and even of Africans but at other moments shows his entirely period-appropriate sense of white superiority in an inconsistent mash that nonetheless feels very human-- as do all of the rest of the characters, except perhaps Gagool.'], [0, 'Excellent read.'], [0, "I'd pick up another Quatermain novel next, if I didn't have a stack of other items on my to-do list!"]]

review_sentences: [[0, '** spoiler alert **'], [0, 'This is a review I wrote for the stage version of Filth, starring Tam Dean Burn, at the time he was the only man ever to play the role.'], [0, 'It says almost everything I want to say about the book, so I thought it was worth reproducing here.'], [0, 'Enjoy:'], [0, "Imagine the best thing you've ever done; imagine the most energy you've ever expended; imagine the ultimate expression of your greatest skill: now multiply that by a one hundred and it's a good bet you still won't even come close to the level of Tam Dean Burn's performance in Filth."], [0, 'His performance is not acting.'], [0, 'It is transformation.'], [0, 'From the moment he struts into his onstage office, briefcase and brown paper bag in hand, lays his first fart and offers advice on how to escape the smell, Tam Dean Burn disappears into the skin and loathsome psyche of Detective Sergeant Bruce Robertson.'], [0, "Robertson - the anti-hero of Harry Gibson's adaptation of Filth, Irvine Welsh's merciless novel of police corruption - is one of the most vile characters ever to hit the stage."], [0, 'He makes Tartuffe and Richard III look like a couple of petulant schoolboys playing tricks on their neighbours.'], [0, "And, more frightening still, he's an invisible monster that walks among us."], [0, "Over the course of a Christmas season Robertson ruins the life of a colleague, starts shagging his friend's wife, battles an intestinal parasite, snorts a whole mess of coke, bites out a guy's tongue, engages in a bloodthirsty act of defenestration, and rapes a girl while his partner busts another for the same crime."], [0, "And this tally only scratches the surface of the sins, bloodshed and hate that find their expression in Burn's uncompromising performance."], [0, 'The degradation of Detective Sergeant Robertson goes well beyond the physical, however.'], [0, "As Tam Dean Burn taps into each of the thirty-two characters that live in Robertson's world and mind we come to realize that this filthy cop is not just evil - he is certifiably mad."], [0, "And Burn internalizes this madness with a physical and mental energy that's humbling to witness, committing himself fully to being Bruce Robertson."], [0, 'Indeed, once onstage, Burn shows no trace at all of the beneficent actor from Leith who fights for equality and peace.'], [0, "All that's left is a beast who shifts from perversion to corruption and back again."], [0, 'Yet, somehow, as with the classic misanthropes that Bruce Robertson eclipses, the audience finds themselves empathizing with the mad Detective Sergeant - and maybe even liking him.'], [0, "And therein lies the true effectiveness of Tam Dean Burn's performance."], [0, "We witness DS Robertson's appalling actions, but Burn makes us believe that somewhere inside, beneath all the hate and anger, a good man, a sane man, is struggling for supremacy."], [0, 'Filth takes us right to the precipice, to the edge of lunacy and horror, and Burn pulls us back.'], [0, "In the hands of a lesser actor Welsh's story could easily spiral out of control."], [0, 'The mirror balls and talking tapeworms, the masturbation and nudity, the ultra violence and disturbing revelations could overwhelm us with hopelessness.'], [0, 'But Tam Dean Burn keeps us with him all the way.'], [0, "He makes us believe in the struggling core of Robertson's goodness, and he shows us that hope can come from even the most tragic events."], [0, 'Filth is not an entertaining play.'], [0, "It's not an easy play to watch."], [0, 'But the questions and ethical dilemmas it raises are relevant to us all.'], [0, 'And it contains the finest stage performance this city has seen.'], [0, 'Tam Dean Burn is unparalleled.'], [0, "It's no wonder Harry Gibson wrote Filth with him in mind."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'I started to get irritated with this book quite quickly and this continued for at least two thirds of the book.'], [0, 'Rosethorn has always been a bit insular but she is not stupid and should have understood early on that Briar would need help with Evvy and the danger they might be in, instead she was so blase about the probable problems she might as well have not been there.'], [0, 'Briar is now 14 years old but he seems to have regressed.'], [0, 'He spends half the book whingeing and seems to be unable to recognise the obvious dangers of a rampant gang war and a vicious scheming power mad noble woman.'], [0, 'Finally in the last quarter of the book Briar seemed to wake up and this became an interesting story.'], [0, 'I would give 2 stars for the first three quarters of the book and 5 stars for the last quarter, which is why I eventually settled on 3.']]

[[0, 'This was a tough read.'], [0, 'Not tough because of long meandering sentences ala Henry James, but tough because of long descriptive passages that elicit nearly no interest in this reader.'], [0, 'I assume that at the time of its publication this book was valued for its vicious criticism of the hypocrisy of various (fictional) members of the British communists and somewhat less pointed criticism of British capitalists, and men (and women) in general.'], [0, 'There are also criticisms of Cold War militarism and racist colonialism.'], [0, 'All of these are more dated than informative.'], [0, 'Somewhat like reading a LIFE magazine from 1944--it does not give you any new information, but it is useful as a window onto the popular outlooks of the time.'], [0, 'For the most part, reading this book was like reading diary entries by an unhappy writer who complains about the persons she interacts with in a prose that is barely leavened with any kind of wit or linguistic pyrotechnics, and which is fairly banal, though meticulous, in its observations.'], [0, "I did greatly enjoy, however, the description of the fictional author's interactions with the British movie and television producers and the American theater producer."], [0, "Her send up of these folks' trivial understanding of her fictional work was very funny and insightful."], [0, 'I also enjoyed the pastiche of newspaper headlines from the ramping up on the Cold War in the 1950s, it being particularly painful to read here at the far end of that paranoid era, when we live with different newer (older) paranoia but are still living with the Cold War fears as well.']]

expected to love this book."], [0, 'I bought a really nice copy of it on impulse a couple years ago, because I just knew it would be awesome, and pretty copies of awesome books are great, right?'], [0, 'I had a feeling it was going to be a while before I would get to it, so when Adam over at Roof Beam Reader started his 2011 TBR Reading Challenge, I thought it would be a great excuse to read review_sentences: [[0, 'As with most other classics in my boyhood days, I watched the film, the 1938 version, before I read the book (though in my defence I did read an abridged, shorter version).'], [0, "So the unforgettable characters, especially Huckleberry Finn and Aunt Polly, and episodes, like the universally famous 'the painting of the fence' chapter, have all been indiscriminately and fondly kept by my memory storing facilities among my own personal experiences in the 'unforgettables' file."], [0, 'In fact, although I have only finished reading the unabridged book today, being nostalgic of one of my all time favourite heroes, I remembered a lot of what the book is all about.'], [0, "It is about recapturing our prized childhood days and all the 'queer enterprises' which we have all engaged in."], [0, "Of course, Twain's distinctive humour and style (and the marvelous illustrations for that matter!)"], [0, 'does help to make the book more engaging and moving.'], [0, 'Many a time did I find myself laughing out loud unexpectedly, which is an astonishing feat for a book written in 1876.'], [0, 'However, having said that, I did find that the second part of the book is basically a repetition of the first; 1) Tom Sawyer gets missing or 2) he overhears a mysterious conversation with Huckleberry Finn which leads to another adventure (in both cases by Injun Joe) and so on.'], [0, 'Everyone who has read the book will understand what I mean although it is not at all a negative factor, so delightful a story it is to read!'], [0, 'All in all, this is a book that should be cherished by families everywhere.'], [0, 'I did find it surprising, truth be told, that no modern film version is available.'], [0, 'I know that would be a challenge considering the times it is set in, but it would be worthwhile.'], [0, 'In this day and age of repetitive video-games and computers, I do feel that it is necessary for boys everywhere to experience a true sense of nature and adventure in their miserable lives.'], [0, 'In the Tom Sawyer tradition, I have always dreamed of one day escaping the boundaries of modern civilization with two fellow and aptly-named adventurers.'], [0, "Maybe I'm not too old yet."], [0, 'Mark Twain is an outstanding author.'], [0, "I do feel that these classics are being neglected by today's young generation, but I also feel that it is also the parents' responsibility to ensure that their children have a adequately stocked library."]]

[[0, 'I LOVE THIS SERIES!!'], [0, "This book is my second favorite of the four, but it's still amazing."], [0, 'The Uglies series was one of my first introductions into the dystopian YA genre, but it still remains one of the best, in my opinion.'], [0, 'Why do I love Uglies so much?'], [0, "Well, first of all, it's very well-written."], [0, "Some of my other favorite books I love for a good plot, good setting, good characters, but not necessarily for the writing...that's not the case with this."], [0, 'Westerfeld can write.'], [0, 'He creates an entire world, down to the small details of things like believable slang and a believable set-up.'], [0, 'Could this scenario actually happen?'], [0, 'I think so.'], [0, "It's not likely, but I could still see it as a possibility, and that's one thing that makes a great dystopian book."], [0, 'I also really like all of the characters.'], [0, "Tally gets a bit irritating at times, especially when it comes to teen-girl things like romance and cattiness, but overall, I'm fond of her."], [0, 'I adore David and his story the best, however, because, well, I just always side with the rebels ;)'], [0, 'Anyone into YA fiction should read at least the first two books of this series!'], [0, '(3 and 4 are less good, but still worth it if you want to know what happens in the end.)']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'One of my favourite lines in film is from Bull Durham.'], [0, 'Annie Savoy (Susan Sarandon) asks Millie how the sex was with Ebby Calvin LaLoosh (Tim Robbins), and Millie says, "He kind of fucks like he throws, sorta all over the place."'], [0, 'And that is EXACTLY how Neil Gaiman writes.'], [0, 'He has mad creative talent.'], [0, 'There is no denying it.'], [0, 'But too often that talent is uncontrolled, chaotic and even bafflingly silly.'], [0, "The Doll's House, written back when he was just becoming Neil Gaiman (and probably had editors forcing his work to be more restrained, which is a scary thought), is packed full of brilliant stuff."], [0, 'The "cereal" convention that turns out to be a convention of serial killers is wicked genius.'], [0, "The cast of characters who make up one of the titular Doll Houses -- Ken and Barbie, the Spider Women, flamboyant Hal, Sandman's missing Fiddler's Green (a landscape of mountains and rivers and foothills turned man), and Rose, the Vortex of Dream -- is fascinating and rich."], [0, "And then there's Rose's brother, the foster boy imprisoned in a basement dungeon for seven years only to be liberated by the nightmare Corinthian; it is a truly chilling scenario (and deserved much more of Gaiman's time)."], [0, "But that's not all ... there's also a brief journey through time to visit an immortal man who rejects death, so he meets Morpheus in a pub that stands on the same spot every hundred years."], [0, "In all of these we see Gaiman's imaginative brilliance."], [0, 'But it is way too much.'], [0, "So much that nothing spooky remains and Gaiman's ability to horrify dissipates with every clever and half-developed new idea he throws at us."], [0, 'Any one of these ideas would have been enough to sustain a seven chapter comic book arc.'], [0, 'Perhaps Gaiman could have used two of the ideas in tandem without things getting out of control, but all of them together is as wild as a mascot dropping, Nuke LaLoosh fastball.'], [0, 'Every time I read Gaiman, I hope I am going to love what I am reading, and there are parts I adore (in The Doll\'s House those things are Dream\'s little family war with Desire, the Collectors and "Men of Good Fortune"), but I always close the cove r frustrated.'], [0, 'Control, control, you must learn control!'], [0, 'Oops, I think I just referenced too many movies.'], [0, "Sorry, but I was reading Gaiman, after all ;) I couldn't help myself."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'As a light read with suspenseful tension throughout, The Moonspinners definitely works.'], [0, "Like another Mary Stewart novel, The Gabriel Hounds, it's also perfect for armchair travelling - Stewart has a way of writing the very atmosphere of exotic locales into her stories in the most wonderfully vivid way."], [0, 'Here, the countryside of Crete comes alive with flower-covered fields on the mountain side, clear waters of the sea, night fishing and a tiny and picturesque village - which makes the horrible human darkness lurking below the scenic beauty all that much more frightening.'], [0, 'The tension holds from the very point our heroine, Nicola Ferris, stumbles upon Mark Langley, a badly wounded young Englishman hiding in the mountains from his would-be murderers.'], [0, "Even though it's almost immediately apparent who the villains must be, given the limited number of characters we're introduced to (and Nicola herself figures it out just as quickly), it's the feeling that you never know quite for sure what exactly they did and how they did it that keeps the suspense going."], [0, "It's too bad that, like The Gabriel Hounds, the tension here mounts to feverish heights by the climax but unfortunately fizzles out once the final action takes place in a rush of scattered and confusing details and ends with a rather flat wrap-up regarding the villains."], [0, "All the strength lies in the lead-up - if you like strong finishes where villains are denounced and dealt with and everything satisfyingly wrapped up, you won't get it here."], [0, "Nicola is just the type of heroine that I like in these novels - she's an independent and intelligent young woman who has the ability to keep her head (at least on the exterior) even in the most unsettling occasions and is certainly no shrinking violet."], [0, "Her tendency to throw herself entirely into potentially dangerous situations is what gets her involved in Mark's predicament in the first place, but she also has the forethought to get herself out of most of those scrapes."], [1, 'Mark is much harder to like - domineering and somewhat chauvinistic, which is again not surprising considering when this was written - and the real downside is that even the indomitable Nicola meets her match in Mark and gets quite girlish about having someone who\'ll "take care of everything."'], [1, "She seemed actually to enjoy Mark's habit of telling her what to do."], [0, "I'm by no means a feminist, but even I found that a little hard to stomach."], [0, 'Not for that reason, but rather because the heroine and love interest spend most of the story apart, I hesitate at the "romantic" part of the romantic suspense label that she\'s known for, though - even considering the time these books were written in (not exactly the period to expect swoony, sweeping romances from), there was very little romance at all.'], [0, "They meet, they interact with little hint of romantic interest, and then... oh hey, it seems they're in love?"], [0, "Nonetheless, it's well worth the read and extremely enjoyable for the excitement and suspense as well as the lovely prose and descriptions of the Greek setting."], [0, "Just don't expect an epic ending or more than a sprinkling of romance."]]
