column2: Lamb: The Gospel According to Biff  Christ's Childhood Pal
review_sentences: [[0, "If only all the Gospels were like Biff's, perhaps the Catholic church would still have its golden claws around my soul."], [0, 'Lucky for me that this gem is a work of fiction, for within the pages of Christopher Moore\'s masterpiece, Jesus Christ, the Lamb of God, the Son, the Prince of Peace, sheds his titles and becomes simply Josh, formally Joshua bar Joseph, firstborn to the same and his wife, Mary, a typical older brother and buddy hanging out in Nazareth and resurrecting his little brother when a game of "Stone the Adulteress" gets a little too enthusiastic.'], [0, 'The story of his life is narrated by the recently corporeal Levi bar Alphaeus who is called Biff, biff being the sound of a hand smacking an irritating child upside the head.'], [0, "Biff has been resurrected into modern Manhattan by Raziel (of Moore's The Stupidest Angel fame) to fill in the thirty year gap in the life of Christ ignored by the current biblical gospels."], [0, 'Alternating between his current reality where he spends most of his time trying to comprehend MTV and other foibles of modern society, and his days with the Son of the Almighty, Biff takes the readers on a a journey over ancient Asia, playing sidekick while Josh seeks out the Wise Men (not kings) who visited him at his birth, and tries to get a handle on his purpose and philosophy as Savior of the world.'], [0, 'On his way, Biff contributes to modern society as well, inventing matches and sarcasm, and describing his sexperiments in such vivid (and horrifying) detail that the Virginal Son of the Lord is all too happy to embrace his requisite celibacy.'], [0, "Interspersed in the narrative are characters well known to the faithful and once-faithful alike, such as the Virgin Mary (local MILF and Biff's intended in the event of Joseph's death), the other, more enticing Mary of Magdala (Maggie), and Simon Peter and the other motley crew of apostles, as well as reintroducing some of Moore's recurring characters--the demon Catch makes an appearance, as does the aforementioned Raziel."], [0, 'Moore uses his sly wit and trademark gross-out humor to cover the serious themes of common threads in major world relgions, the true meaning of the ideals of loyalty and faith, and finally, the compelling power of a second chance.'], [0, 'I laughed so hard I cried, and towards the end, the tears came of their own accord.'], [0, 'For two thousand years the figure of Christ has been examined as God become Man, but Christopher Moore, with his humanizing touch, examines Jesus--and to a lesser extent, the Saints--as Man become God.'], [0, 'The result is his best achievement in an already magnificent body of work, a beautiful, tacky, warped, tragic, witty, warming, divine, flawless, and deeply human comedy.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "After the painful reading experience of Academ's Fury, I secretly hoped that this would be a horrible read so I could just toss all 6 in a pile to be sold (I was given the first three and while reading the first one started purchasing the other 3 because I was so impressed)."], [0, "Well, son of a gun if Jim Butcher hasn't actually written something that wasn't Dresden Files and yet is up to the standard of fun and excitement involved there."], [0, "There's something about the world created in his Codex Alera - a world where magic is a living Fury you form a connection with - that is so believable and well-rounded and vast that I just want to spend more time there."], [0, 'Maybe it\'s the Dune-esque political intrigue mixed with powerfully engaging races - with complex characters that blur black-and-white moralities even while having a few that are Good - set against "upcoming dreadful things" mixed with very well written action sequences that bound between internal struggles and full scale wars.'], [0, "Then again, if you've read Dresden Files ... you know that Jim Butcher's strength (at least on the first read) is the climax."], [0, "Cursor's Fury starts its climax at about page 150 and doesn't stop until 500 some."], [0, "There's no more need for set-up and (unlike Dresden Files) no need to repeat basic facts every book."], [0, "It's clear where the series is going ... and I'm OK with that."], [0, 'I just really want Butcher to stop thinking that Epic Fantasy language starts and ends with switching verbs and subjects around and old cliches (like the response, "And I you" to "I love you").'], [0, 'At least in this book, he did a better job of hiding the "stylistic language" that drove me bonkers last book.'], [0, "Yeah, even though I know this story ... I find the world it takes place in and the characters so engaging that I don't mind being told again."]]

[[0, "Those of you thinking of starting this series because of Butcher's other fantasy novels (Dresden Files), let me warn you right now that this is a different type of novel and Jim Butcher writes it accordingly."], [0, 'For the very fact that it has a completely different tone and air about it, I am pleased.'], [0, 'It shows that Jim Butcher has talent in his writing beyond aping the great noir style he employs in the fantasy-mystery series.'], [0, "Here, he uses his writer's voice to hover above the action, in essence playing to the field of Epic Fantasy."], [0, 'But what he has created in this novel is more than just a neat magic system.'], [0, "He's created a world akin to Larry Niven, Jerry Pournelle and Steven Barnes's book The Legacy of Heorot."], [0, 'That is, we are looking at a world where a natural order exists and, though it is only hinted at here, that natural order exists for a reason.'], [0, "That is exciting and I can imagine many great things that can occur in this world through Butcher's imagination."], [0, "I've seen what he has done in an urban setting, creating this whole world leads me to believe he will deepen it with future books also."], [0, 'So the set-up and writing are strong, but beyond the interesting ideas presented in regards to the world, there is really nothing new here for Fantasy fans (even I, a neophyte to the genre, know this).'], [0, 'More likely than not, even the aspects of the world that I found interesting are not new to the genre.'], [0, 'The characters have, in essence, all been written before.'], [0, 'While the women are strong and fight, they are also used in this novel for a few steamy sex scenes.'], [0, 'If it were one or two, than I could understand it, but every central female character ends up in a sexual situation and for that Jim Butcher should be very careful.'], [0, 'While the original Epic Fantasies could get away with this, we live in a modern age where that type of sexism (as innocent as it may have been) just throws off a lot of folk.'], [0, 'One final note.'], [0, 'The blurbs on both Goodreads and the back of the book focus on the character of Tavi.'], [0, 'The novel, though, uses Tavi and his story as only a third of the plots.'], [0, 'He may be an interesting character, but he is not the central character (that may go to female lead Amara) to the series yet.'], [0, 'Obviously there is major set-up to make him the central character, but at this point he is just a lucky and resourceful character.']]

[[0, 'In 1966 a one-time Hugo awards for the best all time series was given to Isaac Asimov for the Foundation saga.'], [0, 'It is well deserved.'], [0, 'I read this book as a kid, and I remember enjoying it, but reading it now as an adult I came to appreciate the breath of his work, how daring it is, in creating this fictional future history, modeled after historical pattern of the past.'], [0, 'As for the previous books, the third (and originally the last) installment of the series is a collection multiple short stories, each set decades apart from each other, each connected to the previous one to tell the history of the "foundation" over the centuries.'], [0, 'After years of struggle, the Foundation lies in ruins--destroyed by the mutant mind power of the Mule.'], [0, 'But it is rumored that there is a Second Foundation hidden somewhere at the end of the Galaxy, established to preserve the knowledge of mankind through the long centuries of barbarism.'], [0, 'The Mule failed to find it the first time--but now he is certain he knows where it lies.'], [0, 'In the second story, the fate of the Foundation rests on young Arcadia Darell, only fourteen years old and burdened with a terrible secret.'], [0, 'Asimov was well known for his lack of interesting, well rounded, female character.'], [0, 'That was quite common (unfortunately) at the time, and the author recognized his limitation and attributed it to his lack of success with women at the time.'], [0, "After many quite unremarkable female side characters, Second Foundation's Arcadia is a groundbreaking and welcomed change: she is captivating, smart, and well-rounded."], [0, 'She is definitely in control of her life, and in the center stage.'], [0, "She is probably one of the most interesting of Asimov's characters."], [0, "It does not come as a surprise that, of all the Foundation's stories, this is often the favorite one."]]

[[0, 'Eastern Standard Tribe reads so quickly and flows so well that it feels like it must be light weight fluff -- a throw away entertainment and nothing more -- but it doesn\'t take much, only a little thought and a willingness to engage with "dead bodies" and "living flesh," to see that it is much more.'], [0, 'Cory Doctorow is an unrepentant blogger, and it shows in this, his second novel.'], [0, 'His language fizzes and crackles like three bags of Pop Rocks burning their carbonated pleasure on a tongue, popping out computer geek jargon in one line and imaginary pop culture in the next, before spinning off into a welcome tirade full of compelling arguments.'], [0, "One minute Doctorow's revealing truly terrifying insights into the field of mental health, demonstrating how a pseudo-science bent on homogeneity can wield enough power to put people away without due process or any process at all."], [0, "The next he's casually envisioning a mobile, futuristic Napster to rule the highway airwaves with piracy turned privateering."], [0, 'It is sci-fi so successful in its plausibility that it almost ceases to be sci-fi.'], [0, "In Doctorow's future there are cars that run on vodka or fry grease, airplanes with hot tubs, comm sets that nullify texting and turn it into chatting, and circadian tribalism that offers a new system of societal organization just waiting to take over those systems we've long accepted, embraced and grown tired of."], [0, "It's all either already happening or is going to happen."], [0, "And if it doesn't happen it will likely only be because whatever it is has taken another form."], [0, "It's not prophetic, but it is fascinatingly observant."], [0, 'Taken together, Eastern Standard Tribe and Down and Out in the Magic Kingdom suggest that Cory Doctorow has the potential to be a Canadian Philip K. Dick.'], [0, "I can't give much higher praise than that."], [0, "But if you aren't familiar with Dick's work try this equation:"], [0, "A non-nihilistic Chuck Palahniuk - Chuck's always disappointing third act + a smart, sci-fi kick in the ass = Cory Doctorow."], [0, 'Check out how his "Chi is flowing" before they turn one of his books into a movie and taint his prose forever.'], [0, 'He may not be the most literary rat on the ship, but his energy makes him the most likely to escape the scuttle.']]

he hasn't seen her since and is still in love with her."], [0, "He's honest to the reader about his selfishness, possessiveness and manipulation, I actually really liked him."], [0, "Without Sarah in his life, he finds it has little meaning, his love of her turning into an obsession, and I couldn't help but understand his pain as I gradually learnt about their shared past."], [0, 'He talks about love and hate being intertwined, unable to separate them from his image of Sarah.'], [0, 'When he thinks he is writing hate, he finds himself writing love and vice versa.'], [0, 'And it is when he hates himself that he finds himself most self aware and honest.'], [0, "'The sense of unhappiness is so much easier to convey than that of happiness."], [0, 'In misery we seem aware of our own existence, even though it may be in the form of a monstrous egotism: this pain of mine is individual, this nerve that winces belongs to me and to no other.'], [0, 'But happiness annihilates us: we lose our identity.'], [0, 'This part of the book I think I enjoyed more- the part focusing on their relationship and Bendrix as a messed up, jealous man.'], [0, 'Some of his all consuming passion was eloquently written and described, in just a sentence I understood it fully.'], [0, "'I had to touch you with my hands, I had to taste you with my tongue; [[0, "When bartender Billy Wiles finds the note tucked under his windshield wiper asserting that the choice to act or not to act will lead to someone's death, he figures it for a prank."], [0, 'His friend, an off-duty police officer, agrees.'], [0, 'But six hours later, someone has been brutally murdered.'], [0, "So begins Dean Koontz's novel Velocity, and Billy's search for a diabolical killer."], [0, 'Once again, Koontz has written a fast-paced novel that keeps the reader glued to the pages.'], [0, 'At first, Billy must choose whether to involve the police, for which he has a guarded mistrust, or not.'], [0, 'In doing so, he determines the category of the next victim, for as one note states, a "young mother of two" will die if the police are involved.'], [0, 'If Billy avoids the cops, however, the killer will target a "single, middle-aged man no one will miss much."'], [0, 'As the murders progress, however, Billy becomes more and more involved.'], [0, 'Ultimately, he learns that evidence linking him to each murder exists, and he winds up covering up for the killer to keep himself out of the hotseat.'], [0, 'At the same time, Billy seeks to protect his comatose fiancee from the insanity around him.'], [0, 'Surprisingly, the murderer reveals details to him about his loved one that Billy had missed, opening up her world to him and making him more determined to hang on to her.'], [0, 'Although he had been out of touch with the world around him, although he had no friends but only acquaintances, Billy learns to let others into his life.'], [0, 'By the close of the novel, he has reattached himself to the world he had previously dismissed.'], [0, 'As the novel progresses, we learn more information about Billy and why he is so determined to keep out of the police radar.'], [0, 'The killer - inclusion of that storyline took away from an already overburdened plot.'], [0, "Also at this point even though the story is out, you'd think the bad guy would still try to kill her just for spite after she ruined his life, but whatever."], [0, 'So maybe if you care at all about politics (which I most definitely do not), or government conspiracies (again with the not caring), and if you like books that drone on and on and on and on about various government agencies and law firms...and the environment, or if maybe you have a thing for innocent girls half your age or you have a foot fetish, then this is the book for you.'], [0, 'If however, your mind completely disengages with political discussion, or you enjoy reading believable female characters then maybe you should give this one a everyone is finding her and how smart she is to figure stuff out, elude capture, etc... Grantham is an investigative reporter...so he's always you know, investigating and...reporting stuff...there are the corrupt government officials, the clueless local police, he list goes on and on."], [0, 'Each person in this book is really a flat, two-dimensional caricature of a believable person.'], [0, "I already mentioned that I don't enjoy government/legal thrillers."], [0, 'However I can look past that aspect of a story if I care about what happens to the characters.'], [0, "This book doesn't give you enough information or insight into any character to see them as a real person or to care what happens to them."], [0, 'There are two exceptions to this.'], [0, "Callahan's friend Verheek struck me as a believable person."], [0, "He had too many random foils and was trying too hard to do what's right while still messing up to be flat like everyone else."], [0, 'The other exception is the assassin we meet in the opening scenes.'], [0, "While they don't go into background or anything, he was fleshed out enough (practicing accents, mimicking behavior, etc...) to seem real to me."]]

review_sentences: [[0, "[Editing because I slipped into the descriptors of race used in the book, which I shouldn't have done."], [0, 'Not good.]'], [0, "As I said in my brief write-up of the first Lily Bard book, I had to try not to be too critical just because I was comparing this series to Julia Spencer-Fleming's series."], [0, 'The second book was less slight as a mystery, but it had more of the problems that had bothered me in the first, as well as a whole new set.'], [0, 'Firstly, there was the slut-shaming, with Deanna, as before, the chief shamee.'], [0, "It's not just her though, and there's a really odd bit with Pardon's niece, who appears in the karate class, where she's - I don't even remember her belt-level - but she's the most highly qualified in the class, and immediately after saying something about how she respects her for it, Lily is talking about her overly-heavy make-up, her long, long blond hair, and her too-tight exercise clothes which are attracting all the guys' attention."], [0, 'Give me a bloody break.'], [1, "I was thinking about it after and there are two women of roughly Lily's age who aren't dismissed as slutty, and one of them is another rape victim , and the other the never-described-as-in-any-way-sexy but certainly dedicated town doctor, Carrie."], [0, "Then there's Lily herself, who is irresistible to all the decent men in the town, of course, and is leered at by the others."], [0, 'The distinction between the two isn\'t quite as solid as it might be, though, especially when Mysterious Stranger\'s first real conversation with Lily contains "I get a hard-on every time I see you."'], [0, "It was especially messy as Lily had just figured out who he was (from the pictures of him in the news a few years ago), and he'd also figured out who she was, and this implied that he was turned on by her past abduction/rape/torture."], [0, "I don't think this was actually the case, but the whole scene just went very wrong."], [0, 'His story is hardly one that seems likely to make her trust him, but hey - sexy times with no-longer-mysterious still-stranger were apparently irresistible to her too.'], [0, "So, these were not good elements of the book, but then there's the racial question."], [0, "I do understand that the book was published in '97, and that levels of awareness of white (and class) privilege were even lower than they are today."], [0, "It's also got to be difficult to write a book at least in part about racial tension and hatred without giving excessive voice to the racists."], [0, "I'm still not okay with the use of the n-word, which happens several times."], [0, "There's more that's problematic here though, starting with Lily's saying something about how she had been comfortable with the slow pace of change in Shakespeare, as things were pretty okay; some of the black people had good jobs and even nice houses."], [0, "(I do have to rely on memory, meaning I'm probably not quoting accurately, as the app for listening to library digital loans is woeful.)"], [0, 'Ouch.'], [0, "This is pretty basic privilege stuff, but while Lily herself is clearly not racist, and the book shows the real racists as despicable in every way, there's more negative than positive in the overall effect."], [0, '(Again, I am not saying that the author herself is bigoted, just because I feel that the book kind of fails in this area.)'], [0, 'The thing that happens very near the end, which really pulls together everything I think makes this aspect of the book a fail, is spoilery in just about every way it can be.'], [1, 'I could think of no reason for Mookie to die, except for her to be hanging onto life just in order to talk to Lily.'], [1, 'That is - offensive.'], [1, "There's nothing suggesting that Lily should be that important to Mookie, except of course for the fact that Lily went running to ask for Mookie's help (she has a rifle and the targets to prove she's a good shot!)"], [1, 'to save Jack, which led to her death.'], [1, "But Mookie says it's okay, as she got to kill some of the guys who'd murdered her brother."], [1, "So really - Lily has yet another installment of pain, injury, near-death, before getting back to her life, her sexy times with Jack, whatever - while Mookie's dead before Lily gets back to her own hospital bed."], [1, "Look the least bit like the characters of colour are more props to Lily's story than much else?"], [1, 'Yeah, to me it does.'], [0, 'I might have given just one more of the books a try, but then I saw that book 4 is called "Shakespeare\'s Trollop", and the blurb indicated just who gets killed in this one, and - no.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'I chose this novel as my Pre-1800 choice in the 2017 Back to the Classics challenge, since it was published way back in 1778.'], [0, 'Frances Burney wrote Evelina anonymously at a time when novel writing (and reading) was frowned upon.'], [0, "I was thinking, 'I'll bet this was the sort of novel young girls were warned not to read.'"], [0, 'I can guess how parents of that time might have found it time wasting.'], [0, "Burney's language has old fashioned charm, but her subject matter is pretty lightweight."], [0, "Even when I'd got a few hundred pages into it, the storyline seemed to be nothing but socialising and trying to dodge the attention of annoying dudes."], [0, "Several times I almost didn't finish."], [0, 'Not only was nothing much happening, but none of the characters grabbed my sympathy or liking.'], [0, 'In fact, several of them were incredibly obnoxious.'], [0, "Here's a quick summary."], [0, 'Evelina has been brought up by the elderly Reverend Arthur Villars, because her mother died giving birth and her father disowned her.'], [0, "She should have been an heiress of two fortunes, but instead, she's an unknown country rustic."], [0, 'However, family connections want Evelina to make her entrance into the world.'], [0, "Her French grandmother plans to win her fortune on her father's side by proving that the bounder was indeed married to her daughter."], [0, "Evelina, who's been sheltered and innocent, has no idea about the predators and potential corrupting influences she'll find in the big city."], [0, 'The story is told in letters, mostly from her to her beloved guardian.'], [0, "We're told part of her problem was 'too much beauty to escape notice, but too little wealth to be sought.'"], [0, "I've got to say, most of the men are depicted as complete shallow twits."], [0, "They all fall head over heels in love with Evelina at first sight because she's pretty, without knowing or caring what sort of person she is."], [0, 'There are bullies, misogynists, philanderers, creeps and crashing bores.'], [0, "Fanny Burney sure knew how to create unflattering male characters, but I'm not sure that's a good recommendation for her book."], [0, 'These days, Evelina could get a restraining order against a pain in the neck like Sir Clement Willoughby.'], [0, 'One shining exception is Lord Orville, who Evelina thought could do no wrong.'], [0, "She had a huge crush on him from the very start, and called him, 'one who seems formed as a pattern for his fellow creatures.'"], [0, "Whoa, that's strong praise."], [0, 'Would you give your husband or boyfriend such a sweeping compliment?'], [0, "In Orville's case, perhaps it was true though, when you consider his competition."], [0, 'The eighteenth century would have been a tough time to be alive, because everything had to be a certain way.'], [0, 'It was a real cookie cutter generation.'], [0, "You probably wouldn't hear any advice to 'be true to yourself.'"], [0, "They'd be more likely to say, 'Do what she's doing.'"], [0, 'You were obliged to be feminine or masculine, according to your gender, and the rules were unbending.'], [0, "Both Evelina and Villars find Mrs Selwyn's tendency to use sarcasm and satire too forward and manly, whereas nowadays, we'd be more likely to accept that this is just her nature."], [0, "It seems you didn't have to step too far out of line to be considered low-bred or vulgar."], [0, 'Both Evelina and Orville were disgusted when three young men had a conversation about eating, including their extensive knowledge of sauces and dressings.'], [0, 'To them, they came across as gluttons and epicures.'], [0, "To me, they might have been discussing a reality cooking show on TV, and I might've even joined in."], [0, "And then there's Evelina's newfound cousins, the Branghton siblings, who she cringed to be seen with."], [0, 'She was anxious to get rid of Sir Clement, yet still ashamed to have him see her with them.'], [0, "Okay, here's my confession."], [0, "They didn't seem bad enough to warrant that sort of snobbery."], [0, "If you've ever read this book, haven't you come across far worse people than the Branghtons?"], [0, "But Evelina knew the Regency social cues and I don't."], [0, "If I managed to catch a time machine to that era, I'd probably be an outcast in a flash."], [0, 'If you make it to the end, the story turns into a sudden soap opera with all sorts of stunning family revelations I thought were hilarious.'], [0, "For any other book I'd say, 'Come on, no way!'"], [0, "For this one though, my reaction was, 'Something's happening at last.'"], [0, "I'm not overly impressed with Fanny Burney's work based on Evelina, which is said to be her best."], [0, "She might've been revived for a few reasons."], [0, "The age of the book alone gives it a sort of hallowed charm, and she's also someone Jane Austen used to read."], [0, "It's probably a sort of second hand fame, but I'd rather stick to Jane from now on."], [0, "One thing I took from this book is that long, rambling small talk you can't escape from was just as tedious in the eighteenth century as it is in the twenty-first."], [0, 'But to finish off with, here are some quotes.'], [0, "As there were so many pests, I'll grab a couple from them just to show what Evelina had to put up with."], [0, "Sir Clement Willoughby: I'm no advocate for hats."], [0, 'Where there is beauty, they only serve to shade it, and where there is none, they excite a most unavailing curiosity.'], [0, "If you think that's bad, how about this one, from his friend?"], [0, "Lord Merton: I don't know what the devil a woman lives for, after thirty."], [0, "She is only in other folks' way."], [0, "Okay, let's mix it up with a few nicer ones."], [0, 'Evelina: My intentions are never willfully blameable, yet I err perpetually.'], [0, "(There's one thing I have in common with her.)"], [0, 'Villars: A youthful mind is seldom totally free from ambition; to curb that is the first step to contentment, since to diminish expectation is to increase enjoyment.'], [0, "(That's probably the best line in the whole book, and it was over within the first few pages.)"], [0, "I felt inclined to give it three stars just because it's the oldest book by a female author I've ever read, but no, I've got to stick true to my ranking criteria, and I really felt like giving up many, many times."], [0, 'For more book chat and reviews, visit my blog, https://vincereview.blogspot.com.au/']]

[[0, 'Katherine and Michael meet at a party and start dating soon after.'], [0, "They fall hard and fast for each other, and soon they're trying to decide whether or not they should have sex."], [0, "They think that their relationship will last forever, but their parents aren't convinced."], [0, 'Will their love survive a summer apart?'], [0, 'Somehow, in all of my Judy Blume-obsessed adolescence, I missed this book.'], [0, "I mean, I'd obviously heard of it."], [0, "(I think everybody's heard of it.)"], [0, 'But somehow I never bought it.'], [0, 'I never even checked it out from the library.'], [0, "But I fixed that last weekend when I couldn't sleep and found it on Overdrive."], [0, "It's hard to rate a book like this."], [0, 'Because, on the one hand, I think it had to have been a really important book for its time.'], [0, "It's so realistic."], [0, 'Michael is kind of a jerk, like many teenage boys.'], [0, "(I probably wouldn't have thought that if I read this as a teenager.)"], [0, 'Katherine is kind of boring, like many teenage girls.'], [0, "(I probably wouldn't have thought that, either.)"], [0, "They decide together that they want to have sex, and that's pretty much what their relationship then revolves around."], [0, "There's a frank discussion of birth control and STDs."], [0, "One of Katherine's friends gets pregnant, and while she has the option of abortion, she decides to have the baby."], [0, "One of Michael's friends tries to deal with accepting the fact that he's gay."], [0, "Katherine's grandmother is a huge fan of Planned Parenthood and leaves Katherine pamphlets about contraception."], [0, 'Much like real life, nothing dramatic happens as a result of these kids having sex.'], [0, 'It just kind of happens.'], [0, 'All of this is great.'], [0, 'But then, on the other hand, this book is really boring.'], [0, "Maybe it's the writing style."], [0, "I don't remember Judy Blume's writing being so full... of ellipses... But they're everywhere here."], [0, "And it makes you feel like... maybe the characters... are kind of dumb... because they can't... finish a thought... without trailing off."], [0, "There's also zero chemistry between these characters."], [0, "I can't figure out what Katherine and Michael actually like about each other, aside from their apparent sexual attraction."], [0, 'They attend different schools.'], [0, "They don't really have any friends in common."], [0, "They don't share any hobbies."], [0, "I didn't really date in high school, so maybe that's what it's actually like."], [0, "I wouldn't know."], [0, 'But this ended up being just another thing that added to my boredom.'], [0, "I just didn't feel at all engaged while I was reading."], [0, "The only other Judy Blume book that I've read recently was"], [0, 'In the Unlikely Event'], [0, 'And while I was reading that, I kept thinking that now that I live in New Jersey, I get a totally different vibe while reading her books.'], [0, "I don't think I ever really noticed when I was little in Wisconsin, but Judy Blume brings New Jersey to life in her books!"], [0, 'As I was reading Forever, just like when I was reading In the Unlikely Event, I kept thinking, "Hey, I\'ve been there!"'], [0, "And regardless of how much I enjoy a book, it's really cool to read something that takes place somewhere you've actually been."], [0, 'I think that, had I read this book when I was younger, I would have really liked it.'], [0, 'I probably would have been heartbroken at how "forever" doesn\'t always last forever.'], [0, 'I probably would have known a little bit more about the ways of the world before I got out on my own.'], [0, 'In the end, I guess I have to figure out if I should rate based on the importance of this book or based on how much I actually liked it.'], [0, 'I think three stars would be a fair compromise.']]

review_sentences: [[0, "It's a quick read but ultimately a bit thin for it."], [0, 'Apparently America survives the nuclear holocaust by reverting to the rules and mores of the Wild West.'], [0, 'Randy Bragg, our protagonist and erstwhile hero, is mouldering in his home town, a failed attempt at a political career behind him, his morning coffee laced with his morning bourbon the only thing getting him from day to day.'], [0, 'He needs something to shake him out of the doldrums he finds himself in.'], [0, 'Rather than a change of scene or career the making of him turns out to be the end of the world.'], [0, 'It seems a rather clunky, by modern standards, metaphor for the United States itself.'], [0, 'Frank reaches back to the ideals of Republican small town America, the sense of community with a strong hand at the helm.'], [0, "There are bad people out there, which helps to bring people under the umbrella of Randy's leadership."], [0, 'Interestingly while what is left of the Government has declared martial law, a role our hero is happy to fall into, luckily being an Air Force reserve officer, nobody suggests holding local elections for the new leadership.'], [0, 'In fact the comparison between the graft and dirty tricks of the incumbent state senate representative and the role Randy is able to play after The Day is worth noting.'], [0, 'While a leader, like Randy, with the good of the community, of the people around him, at heart is extolled as a good thing, little is made of what would happen to Fort Repose if Porky Logan had been around to take the reins.'], [0, 'In order to regain a life worth living they retreat into a bucolic utopia, maintained with will, a bit of grit and good old fashioned US know-how.'], [0, "They lose contact with the outside world because they run out of petrol and can't charge the batteries, no matter that they have a river and could make a waterwheel to fill the job."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'The start of a great new world'], [0, 'I gave this book four stars, yet would have rather placed it at 3.5.'], [0, "For the first book in a series, it shows a lot of promise, especially in comparison to a few other freshman entries I've read recently like 'Mark of the Demon', however, it is a freshman novel and carries a lot of the problems that goes a long with it."], [0, "The main character, Kate, is very well developed and a heroine with enough guts and edge that make her easy to route for, the problem is that the novel invests far too much time introducing lesser characters that really don't get their time to shine (in this book anyway)."], [0, "This leads to a lot of 'who's this again?"], [0, "'s' when reading and I found myself having to backtrack a little to remember, particularly towards the end where some minor characters die."], [0, 'I often found myself clearly not caring as much as the author intended.'], [0, 'Another problem/plus of the novel is the world the author has created.'], [0, 'A lot of these urban fantasy novels create supernatural worlds that are all similar, but with this novel the author has created something quite unique that actually garnered my attention.'], [0, 'It being the first book however, I did find myself somewhat confused at points as to what was exactly going on.'], [0, "I'm sure this problem will be solved though when reading the rest of the series and learning more of the mythology and technicalities of the world."], [0, 'Overall, a very good effort at the start of a series and an freshman effort that kept me wanting more.'], [0, "This has left it as one of the few series I've began lately where I actually look forward to reading the sequel, and one that I would recommend to anyone interested in the genre."]]

review_sentences: [[0, 'Review of The Shadow of the Torturer (Part 1 of Shadow and Claw): Gene Wolfe and the New Sun series appears on a lot of must-read lists.'], [0, 'so I got around to reading the first book.'], [0, 'I did read this in conjunction with a Goodreads science-fiction and fantasy book club.'], [0, 'The responses to The Shadow of the Torturer fell into two camps, broadly speaking.'], [0, 'I fell into the "enjoyed it camp."'], [0, 'The book is not an easy read.'], [0, 'Why?'], [0, "Wolfe writes in a postmodern vein, which is a way of saying that if you are seeking clarity in plot, characters, and motivations, you won't find it here."], [0, 'That is not saying Wolfe does not provide a plot and whatnot, but he constantly undermines all of it by wordplay, ambiguity, and confusion.'], [0, 'Instead, you constantly question yourself, what you know because--at least for me--the essential question of postmodernism is can you anything truly.'], [0, 'So the language subverts what we can know, and Wolfe uses a plethora of antique words: carnifex, amphitryon, gyoll, noyade, and on and on.'], [0, "If you don't like using a dictionary (and an excellent dictionary) this book may not be of interest to you."], [0, 'As a part of that, the appendix promotes a postmodern reading of this book.'], [0, "You begin the novel and, if you're like me, pulling out the dictionary to check meanings on many out-of-date terms."], [0, 'The story adds layers upon layers and never allows you to have a settled perception.'], [0, 'Then comes the appendix, which throws another layer on it.'], [0, 'The "translator" of Severian\'s tale found proximate words or, in the case of Latin terms, crafted something for unknown words.'], [0, "In other words, a lot of the words you've been hanging onto to allow for comprehension, Wolfe pretty much blows up."], [0, 'What you thought you knew may not be what you thought you knew.'], [0, 'Though it could be still.'], [0, 'Sometimes even the characters seem confused by the terminology or events.'], [0, 'All of this is subtly told.'], [0, 'Plot: Severian, a journeyman in the guild of torturers, is exiled from the city Nessus for a crime against the guild.'], [0, "By the end of the novel, Severian has encountered a number of characters and some exploits, and arrives at a giant wall and gate without much in between--yet it's a hefty 600 some pages (ebook)."], [0, 'Wolfe is a masterful writer with a stunning grasp of English and the multiplicity of meanings (historical and popular) that words have, a way reminiscent of Vladimir Nabokov (a writer I greatly admire).'], [0, 'This is a novel that will stand up to multiple readings because the smallest of details, the smallest of perceptions of not only the reader but the characters open up entirely new avenues of meaning.'], [0, 'A highly recommended novel.']]

review_sentences: [[0, 'Any reading and review of this classic science fiction polemic on the state of the environment has to be done through the prism of the time it was written in the early 70s.'], [0, 'Set in a dystopian future from that time, likely some time in the 80s the themes of the time it was written are laced throughout.'], [0, "Both the fear of communism and socialism, racism, as well as the concept of the draft and military service are dealt with prominantly, whilst more modern concerns of todays society such as the use and behaviour of the media, government surveillance and warmongering foreign policy don't really show up here."], [0, 'The environmentalist message that provides the core of the problems for the world in this book also concentrates more on the impact of chemicals, health problems caused by pollution and the growing immunities of bugs, both large and microscopic, to insecticides and anitbiotics.'], [0, "Interestingly the concept of climate change and global warming aren't even really hinted at."], [0, 'The style of writing the author uses is interesting in itself.'], [0, 'At first seemingly random, dealing with disperate characters and events around the globe; An African aid worker, A policeman and his wife worrying about bringing a child into a world that leaves so many new children sickly and disabled, an insurance broker, the son of a wealthy philanthropist and the former leader of a political movement that has since grown into what is effectively a terrorist group.'], [0, 'Interspersed with the longer sections with these characters and others that come and go, are little snap shots of songs, media reports, poems and vignettes that slowly reveal more and more of the world we are reading about.'], [0, "It's an effective technique I found and I enjoyed the slow reveal."], [0, 'That said, I found it heavy going at times in the first half, struggling to keep straight the different characters and understanding the places the events were happening in.'], [0, 'I suspect it was done on purpose like that as some people you thought were important to the story were never heard from again or brutally killed off.'], [0, 'Sticking with it though proved to be a rewarding experience to me.'], [0, 'The groundwork put in in the first half left me unsure what was going to happen and who would survive.'], [0, 'The author was ruthless in his protrayal of the slow, then rapid disintigration of the world he had created.'], [0, 'It is to the credit of the authors vision and writing that even forty years later the description of the collapse of American society seems so plausible and real.'], [0, "The marvellous extended chapter towards the end of the book that jumps all overt he place acting almost as a montage shows just how brutal a world poisoned by it's own excessive consumption can be as it begins to die."], [0, "It's a terrific piece of writing."], [0, 'My skin was actually crawling as health issue after health issue was shown affecting more and more of the population cumulating in the mass hallucinogenic riots in Denver and the trial of Austin Train.'], [0, "A terrific read that rewards perseverance through the tough early section and it's a book that seems to have more relevence now than it may have done when it was written."], [0, "I've read people talking about the ending being a little anticlimatic, but I can't knock any ending that made me smile as much as this one did."], [0, "The solution proposed by the man who had created a computer simulation of the world to understand the problems it had first makes you laugh then makes you wonder with horror whether it might apply even more urgently to society today than it might have in the case you've just read."], [1, '"We can just about restore the balance of the ecology, the biosphere, and so on-in other words we can live within our means instead of on an unrepayable overdraft, as we\'ve been doing for the past half
